Put a #large saucepan{} of water on to boil. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel). Trim the root and the dark green leafy part from the @leeks{2}. Halve lengthways then thinly slice widthways. Add the potato to the pan of boiling water and simmer until cooked, ~{15-20%minutes}. 

> The potato is cooked when you can easily slip a knife through. Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} and keep to one side.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{2%tbsp} in a #wide bottomed saucepan{} on medium heat. Add the leek and cook, stirring frequently, ~{5%minutes}. 

> You want it to soften and not brown. Meanwhile, roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1/2%bunch}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all).

Add the @vegetable stock powder{1} to the leek along with the @water{150%ml}. Stir to dissolve the stock powder, then reduce the heat to low and leave to simmer until the stock has reduced by half, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Meanwhile, cut each @goat's cheese{125%g} log into four slices per person. Keep to one side. Combine the @grated hard Italian style cheese{40%g} with the @panko breadcrumbs{30%g} in a #small bowl{}. Season with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @ground black pepper{pinch} then mix in the olive oil. Keep to one side. Preheat your #grill{} to its highest setting.

Add the @baby spinach{125%g} to your leek mixture, stir and cook for a further ~{2%minutes} to make sure it wilts. Your potato should be cooked and drained by now, add it to the pan as well. Sprinkle in the parsley and then stir in the @creme fraiche{100%g}. Lower the heat and warm until the crème fraîche starts to bubble. Remove from the heat and taste the mixture. Add some salt and pepper if necessary.

Spoon the mixture into an #ovenproof dish{} and sprinkle the cheesy breadcrumbs on top. Finish with the goat's cheese slices and pop under your grill for ~{3-5%minutes}. You want the goat's cheese to melt and the crumb to brown nicely.

> Keep an eye on it - you don't want to burn the crust! Serve your leek and potato gratin in deep bowls. Enjoy!